v8
V8 is Googleâ€™s open source high-performance JavaScript and WebAssembly engine, written in C++. It is used in Chrome and in Node.js, among others. It implements ECMAScript and WebAssembly, and runs on Windows, macOS, and Linux systems that use x64, IA-32, or ARM processors. V8 can be embedded into any C++ application.

84// DEFINING NEW OPERATIONS
85// =======================
86// For each operation `Foo`, we define:
87// - An entry V(Foo) in one of the TURBOSHAFT*OPERATION list (eg,
88// TURBOSHAFT_OPERATION_LIST_BLOCK_TERMINATOR,
89// TURBOSHAFT_SIMPLIFIED_OPERATION_LIST etc), which defines
90// `Opcode::kFoo` and whether the operation is a block terminator.
91// - A `struct FooOp`, which derives from either `OperationT<FooOp>` or
92// `FixedArityOperationT<k, FooOp>` if the op always has excactly `k` inputs.
93// Furthermore, the struct has to contain:
94// - A bunch of options directly as public fields.
95// - A getter `options()` returning a tuple of all these options. This is used
96// for default printing and hashing. Alternatively, `void
97// PrintOptions(std::ostream& os) const` and `size_t hash_value() const` can
98// also be defined manually.
99// - Getters for named inputs.
100// - A constructor that first takes all the inputs and then all the options. For
101// a variable arity operation where the constructor doesn't take the inputs as
102// a single base::Vector<OpIndex> argument, it's also necessary to overwrite
103// the static `New` function, see `CallOp` for an example.
104// - An `Explode` method that unpacks an operation and invokes the passed
105// callback. If the operation inherits from FixedArityOperationT, the base
106// class already provides the required implementation.
107// - `OpEffects` as either a static constexpr member `effects` or a
108// non-static method `Effects()` if the effects depend on the particular
109// operation and not just the opcode.
110// - outputs_rep/inputs_rep methods, which should return a vector describing the
111// representation of the outputs and inputs of this operations.
112// After defining the struct here, you'll also need to integrate it in
113// Turboshaft:
114// - If Foo is not in not lowered before reaching the instruction selector, add
115// a overload of ProcessOperation for FooOp in recreate-schedule.cc, and
116// handle Opcode::kFoo in the Turboshaft VisitNode of instruction-selector.cc.
117

401#define COUNT_OPCODES(Name) +1
402constexpr uint16_t kNumberOfBlockTerminatorOpcodes =
403 0 TURBOSHAFT_OPERATION_LIST_BLOCK_TERMINATOR(COUNT_OPCODES);
404#undef COUNT_OPCODES
405
406#define COUNT_OPCODES(Name) +1

408 0 TURBOSHAFT_OPERATION_LIST(COUNT_OPCODES);
409#undef COUNT_OPCODES

411inline constexpr bool IsBlockTerminator(Opcode opcode) {
412 return OpcodeIndex(opcode) < kNumberOfBlockTerminatorOpcodes;
413}

421#define TURBOSHAFT_THROWING_OPERATIONS_LIST(V) \

426// Operations that need to be followed by `DidntThrowOp`.
427inline constexpr bool MayThrow(Opcode opcode) {
428#define CASE(Name) case Opcode::k##Name:
429 switch (opcode) {
430 TURBOSHAFT_THROWING_OPERATIONS_LIST(CASE)
431 return true;
432 default:
433 return false;
434 }
435#undef CASE
436}

438// For Throwing operations, outputs_rep() are empty, because the values are
439// produced by the subsequent DidntThrow. Nevertheless, the operation has to
440// define its output representations in an array that DidntThrow can then reuse
441// to know what its outputs are. Additionally, when using Maglev as a frontend,
442// catch handlers that have never been reach so far are not emitted, and instead
443// the throwing operations lazy deopt instead of throwing.
444//
445// That's where the THROWING_OP_BOILERPLATE macro comes in: it creates an array
446// of representations that DidntThrow can use, and will define outputs_rep() to
447// be empty, and takes care of creating a LazyDeoptOnThrow member. For instance:
448//
449// THROWING_OP_BOILERPLATE(RegisterRepresentation::Tagged(),
450// RegisterRepresentation::Word32())
451//
452// Warning: don't forget to add `lazy_deopt_on_throw` to the `options` of your
453// Operation (you'll get a compile-time error if you forget it).
454#define THROWING_OP_BOILERPLATE(...) \
455 static constexpr RegisterRepresentation kOutputRepsStorage[]{__VA_ARGS__}; \
456 static constexpr base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> kOutReps = \
457 base::VectorOf(kOutputRepsStorage, arraysize(kOutputRepsStorage)); \
458 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const { \
459 return {}; \
460 } \
461 LazyDeoptOnThrow lazy_deopt_on_throw;
462
463template <typename T>
464inline base::Vector<T> InitVectorOf(
465 ZoneVector<T>& storage,
466 std::initializer_list<RegisterRepresentation> values) {
467 storage.resize(values.size());
468 size_t i = 0;
469 for (auto&& value : values) {
470 storage[i++] = value;
471 }
472 return base::VectorOf(storage);
473}

475class InputsRepFactory {
476 public:
477 constexpr static base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> SingleRep(
478 RegisterRepresentation rep) {
479 return base::VectorOf(ToMaybeRepPointer(rep), 1);
480 }
481
482 constexpr static base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> PairOf(
483 RegisterRepresentation rep) {
484 return base::VectorOf(ToMaybeRepPointer(rep), 2);
485 }
486
487 protected:
488 constexpr static const MaybeRegisterRepresentation* ToMaybeRepPointer(
489 RegisterRepresentation rep) {
490 size_t index = static_cast<size_t>(rep.value()) * 2;
491 DCHECK_LT(index, arraysize(rep_map));
492 return &rep_map[index];
493 }
494
495 private:
496 constexpr static MaybeRegisterRepresentation rep_map[] = {
497 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Word32(),
498 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Word32(),
499 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
500 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
501 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Float32(),
502 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Float32(),
503 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Float64(),
504 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Float64(),
505 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Tagged(),
506 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Tagged(),
507 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Compressed(),
508 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Compressed(),
509 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Simd128(),
510 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Simd128(),
511#ifdef V8_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD256_REVEC
512 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Simd256(),
513 MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Simd256(),
514#endif // V8_ENABLE_WASM_SIMD256_REVEC
515 };
516};
517
518struct EffectDimensions {
519 // Produced by loads, consumed by operations that should not move before loads
520 // because they change memory.
521 bool load_heap_memory : 1;
522 bool load_off_heap_memory : 1;
523
524 // Produced by stores, consumed by operations that should not move before
525 // stores because they load or store memory.
526 bool store_heap_memory : 1;
527 bool store_off_heap_memory : 1;
528
529 // Operations that perform raw heap access (like initialization) consume
530 // `before_raw_heap_access` and produce `after_raw_heap_access`.
531 // Operations that need the heap to be in a consistent state produce
532 // `before_raw_heap_access` and consume `after_raw_heap_access`.
533 bool before_raw_heap_access : 1;
534 // Produced by operations that access raw/untagged pointers into the
535 // heap or keep such a pointer alive, consumed by operations that can GC to
536 // ensure they don't move before the raw access.
537 bool after_raw_heap_access : 1;
538
539 // Produced by any operation that can affect whether subsequent operations are
540 // executed, for example by branching, deopting, throwing or aborting.
541 // Consumed by all operations that should not be hoisted before a check
542 // because they rely on it. For example, loads usually rely on the shape of
543 // the heap object or the index being in bounds.
544 bool control_flow : 1;
545 // We need to ensure that the padding bits have a specified value, as they are
546 // observable in bitwise operations.
547 uint8_t unused_padding : 1;
548
549 using Bits = uint8_t;
550 constexpr EffectDimensions()
551 : load_heap_memory(false),
552 load_off_heap_memory(false),
553 store_heap_memory(false),
554 store_off_heap_memory(false),
555 before_raw_heap_access(false),
556 after_raw_heap_access(false),
557 control_flow(false),
558 unused_padding(0) {}
559 Bits bits() const { return base::bit_cast<Bits>(*this); }
560 static EffectDimensions FromBits(Bits bits) {
561 return base::bit_cast<EffectDimensions>(bits);
562 }
563 bool operator==(EffectDimensions other) const {
564 return bits() == other.bits();
565 }
566 bool operator!=(EffectDimensions other) const {
567 return bits() != other.bits();
568 }
569};
570static_assert(sizeof(EffectDimensions) == sizeof(EffectDimensions::Bits));
571
572// Possible reorderings are restricted using two bit vectors: `produces` and
573// `consumes`. Two operations cannot be reordered if the first operation
574// produces an effect dimension that the second operation consumes. This is not
575// necessarily symmetric. For example, it is possible to reorder
576// Load(x)
577// CheckMaps(y)
578// to become
579// CheckMaps(x)
580// Load(y)
581// because the load cannot affect the map check. But the other direction could
582// be unsound, if the load depends on the map check having been executed. The
583// former reordering is useful to push a load across a check into a branch if
584// it is only needed there. The effect system expresses this by having the map
585// check produce `EffectDimensions::control_flow` and the load consuming
586// `EffectDimensions::control_flow`. If the producing operation comes before the
587// consuming operation, then this order has to be preserved. But if the
588// consuming operation comes first, then we are free to reorder them. Operations
589// that produce and consume the same effect dimension always have a fixed order
590// among themselves. For example, stores produce and consume the store
591// dimensions. It is possible for operations to be reorderable unless certain
592// other operations appear in-between. This way, the IR can be generous with
593// reorderings as long as all operations are high-level, but become more
594// restrictive as soon as low-level operations appear. For example, allocations
595// can be freely reordered. Tagged bitcasts can be reordered with other tagged
596// bitcasts. But a tagged bitcast cannot be reordered with allocations, as this
597// would mean that an untagged pointer can be alive while a GC is happening. The
598// way this works is that allocations produce the `before_raw_heap_access`
599// dimension and consume the `after_raw_heap_access` dimension to stay either
600// before or after a raw heap access. This means that there are no ordering
601// constraints between allocations themselves. Bitcasts should not
602// be moved accross an allocation. We treat them as raw heap access by letting
603// them consume `before_raw_heap_access` and produce `after_raw_heap_access`.
604// This way, allocations cannot be moved across bitcasts. Similarily,
605// initializing stores and uninitialized allocations are classified as raw heap
606// access, to prevent any operation that relies on a consistent heap state to be
607// scheduled in the middle of an inline allocation. As long as we didn't lower
608// to raw heap accesses yet, pure allocating operations or operations reading
609// immutable memory can float freely. As soon as there are raw heap accesses,
610// they become more restricted in their movement. Note that calls are not the
611// most side-effectful operations, as they do not leave the heap in an
612// inconsistent state, so they do not need to be marked as raw heap access.
613struct OpEffects {
614 EffectDimensions produces;
615 EffectDimensions consumes;
616
617 // Operations that cannot be merged because they produce identity. That is,
618 // every repetition can produce a different result, but the order in which
619 // they are executed does not matter. All we care about is that they are
620 // different. Producing a random number or allocating an object with
621 // observable pointer equality are examples. Producing identity doesn't
622 // restrict reordering in straight-line code, but we must prevent using GVN or
623 // moving identity-producing operations in- or out of loops.
624 bool can_create_identity : 1;
625 // If the operation can allocate and therefore can trigger GC.
626 bool can_allocate : 1;
627 // Instructions that have no uses but are `required_when_unused` should not be
628 // removed.
629 bool required_when_unused : 1;
630 // We need to ensure that the padding bits have a specified value, as they are
631 // observable in bitwise operations. This is split into two fields so that
632 // also MSVC creates the correct object layout.
633 uint8_t unused_padding_1 : 5;
634 uint8_t unused_padding_2;
635
636 constexpr OpEffects()
637 : can_create_identity(false),
638 can_allocate(false),
639 required_when_unused(false),
640 unused_padding_1(0),
641 unused_padding_2(0) {}
642
643 using Bits = uint32_t;
644 Bits bits() const { return base::bit_cast<Bits>(*this); }
645 static OpEffects FromBits(Bits bits) {
646 return base::bit_cast<OpEffects>(bits);
647 }
648
649 bool operator==(OpEffects other) const { return bits() == other.bits(); }
650 bool operator!=(OpEffects other) const { return bits() != other.bits(); }
651 OpEffects operator|(OpEffects other) const {
652 return FromBits(bits() | other.bits());
653 }
654 OpEffects operator&(OpEffects other) const {
655 return FromBits(bits() & other.bits());
656 }
657 bool IsSubsetOf(OpEffects other) const {
658 return (bits() & ~other.bits()) == 0;
659 }
660
661 constexpr OpEffects AssumesConsistentHeap() const {
662 OpEffects result = *this;
663 // Do not move the operation into a region with raw heap access.
664 result.produces.before_raw_heap_access = true;
665 result.consumes.after_raw_heap_access = true;
666 return result;
667 }
668 // Like `CanAllocate()`, but allocated values must be immutable and not have
669 // identity (for example `HeapNumber`).
670 // Note that if we first allocate something as mutable and later make it
671 // immutable, we have to allocate it with identity.
672 constexpr OpEffects CanAllocateWithoutIdentity() const {
673 OpEffects result = AssumesConsistentHeap();
674 result.can_allocate = true;
675 return result;
676 }
677 // Allocations change the GC state and can trigger GC, as well as produce a
678 // fresh identity.
679 constexpr OpEffects CanAllocate() const {
680 return CanAllocateWithoutIdentity().CanCreateIdentity();
681 }
682 // The operation can leave the heap in an incosistent state or have untagged
683 // pointers into the heap as input or output.
684 constexpr OpEffects CanDoRawHeapAccess() const {
685 OpEffects result = *this;
686 // Do not move any operation that relies on a consistent heap state accross.
687 result.produces.after_raw_heap_access = true;
688 result.consumes.before_raw_heap_access = true;
689 return result;
690 }
691 // Reading mutable heap memory. Reading immutable memory doesn't count.
692 constexpr OpEffects CanReadHeapMemory() const {
693 OpEffects result = *this;
694 result.produces.load_heap_memory = true;
695 // Do not reorder before stores.
696 result.consumes.store_heap_memory = true;
697 return result;
698 }
699 // Reading mutable off-heap memory or other input. Reading immutable memory
700 // doesn't count.
701 constexpr OpEffects CanReadOffHeapMemory() const {
702 OpEffects result = *this;
703 result.produces.load_off_heap_memory = true;
704 // Do not reorder before stores.
705 result.consumes.store_off_heap_memory = true;
706 return result;
707 }
708 // Writing any off-memory or other output.
709 constexpr OpEffects CanWriteOffHeapMemory() const {
710 OpEffects result = *this;
711 result.required_when_unused = true;
712 result.produces.store_off_heap_memory = true;
713 // Do not reorder before stores.
714 result.consumes.store_off_heap_memory = true;
715 // Do not reorder before loads.
716 result.consumes.load_off_heap_memory = true;
717 // Do not move before deopting or aborting operations.
718 result.consumes.control_flow = true;
719 return result;
720 }
721 // Writing heap memory that existed before the operation started. Initializing
722 // newly allocated memory doesn't count.
723 constexpr OpEffects CanWriteHeapMemory() const {
724 OpEffects result = *this;
725 result.required_when_unused = true;
726 result.produces.store_heap_memory = true;
727 // Do not reorder before stores.
728 result.consumes.store_heap_memory = true;
729 // Do not reorder before loads.
730 result.consumes.load_heap_memory = true;
731 // Do not move before deopting or aborting operations.
732 result.consumes.control_flow = true;
733 return result;
734 }
735 // Writing any memory or other output, on- or off-heap.
736 constexpr OpEffects CanWriteMemory() const {
737 return CanWriteHeapMemory().CanWriteOffHeapMemory();
738 }
739 // Reading any memory or other input, on- or off-heap.
740 constexpr OpEffects CanReadMemory() const {
741 return CanReadHeapMemory().CanReadOffHeapMemory();
742 }
743 // The operation might read immutable data from the heap, so it can be freely
744 // reordered with operations that keep the heap in a consistent state. But we
745 // must prevent the operation from observing an incompletely initialized
746 // object.
747 constexpr OpEffects CanReadImmutableMemory() const {
748 OpEffects result = AssumesConsistentHeap();
749 return result;
750 }
751 // Partial operations that are only safe to execute after we performed certain
752 // checks, for example loads may only be safe after a corresponding bound or
753 // map checks.
754 constexpr OpEffects CanDependOnChecks() const {
755 OpEffects result = *this;
756 result.consumes.control_flow = true;
757 return result;
758 }
759 // The operation can affect control flow (like branch, deopt, throw or crash).
760 constexpr OpEffects CanChangeControlFlow() const {
761 OpEffects result = *this;
762 result.required_when_unused = true;
763 // Signal that this changes control flow. Prevents stores or operations
764 // relying on checks from flowing before this operation.
765 result.produces.control_flow = true;
766 // Stores must not flow past something that affects control flow.
767 result.consumes.store_heap_memory = true;
768 result.consumes.store_off_heap_memory = true;
769 return result;
770 }
771 // Execution of the current function may end with this operation, for example
772 // because of return, deopt, exception throw or abort/trap.
773 constexpr OpEffects CanLeaveCurrentFunction() const {
774 // All memory becomes observable.
775 return CanChangeControlFlow().CanReadMemory().RequiredWhenUnused();
776 }
777 // The operation can deopt.
778 constexpr OpEffects CanDeopt() const {
779 return CanLeaveCurrentFunction()
780 // We might depend on previous checks to avoid deopting.
781 .CanDependOnChecks();
782 }
783 // Producing identity doesn't prevent reorderings, but it prevents GVN from
784 // de-duplicating identical operations.
785 constexpr OpEffects CanCreateIdentity() const {
786 OpEffects result = *this;
787 result.can_create_identity = true;
788 return result;
789 }
790 // The set of all possible effects.
791 constexpr OpEffects CanCallAnything() const {
792 return CanReadMemory()
793 .CanWriteMemory()
794 .CanAllocate()
795 .CanChangeControlFlow()
796 .CanDependOnChecks()
797 .RequiredWhenUnused();
798 }
799 constexpr OpEffects RequiredWhenUnused() const {
800 OpEffects result = *this;
801 result.required_when_unused = true;
802 return result;
803 }
804
805 // Operations that can be removed if their result is not used. Unused
806 // allocations can be removed.
807 constexpr bool is_required_when_unused() const {
808 return required_when_unused;
809 }
810 // Operations that can be moved before a preceding branch or check.
811 bool hoistable_before_a_branch() const {
812 // Since this excludes `CanDependOnChecks()`, most loads actually cannot be
813 // hoisted.
814 return IsSubsetOf(OpEffects().CanReadMemory());
815 }
816 // Operations that can be eliminated via value numbering, which means that if
817 // there are two identical operations where one dominates the other, then the
818 // second can be replaced with the first one. This is safe for deopting or
819 // throwing operations, because the absence of read effects guarantees
820 // deterministic behavior.
821 bool repetition_is_eliminatable() const {
822 return IsSubsetOf(OpEffects()
823 .CanDependOnChecks()
824 .CanChangeControlFlow()
825 .CanAllocateWithoutIdentity());
826 }
827 bool can_read_mutable_memory() const {
828 return produces.load_heap_memory | produces.load_off_heap_memory;
829 }
830 bool requires_consistent_heap() const {
831 return produces.before_raw_heap_access | consumes.after_raw_heap_access;
832 }
833 bool can_write() const {
834 return produces.store_heap_memory | produces.store_off_heap_memory;
835 }
836 bool can_be_constant_folded() const {
837 // Operations that CanDependOnChecks can still be constant-folded. If they
838 // did indeed depend on a check, then their result will only be used after
839 // said check has been executed anyways.
840 return IsSubsetOf(OpEffects().CanDependOnChecks());
841 }
842};
843static_assert(sizeof(OpEffects) == sizeof(OpEffects::Bits));
844
845V8_INLINE size_t hash_value(OpEffects effects) {
846 return static_cast<size_t>(effects.bits());
847}
848
849inline bool CannotSwapOperations(OpEffects first, OpEffects second) {
850 return first.produces.bits() & (second.consumes.bits());
851}
852
853V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
854 OpEffects op_effects);
855
856// SaturatedUint8 is a wrapper around a uint8_t, which can be incremented and
857// decremented with the `Incr` and `Decr` methods. These methods prevent over-
858// and underflow, and saturate once the uint8_t reaches the maximum (255):
859// future increment and decrement will not change the value then.
860// We purposefuly do not expose the uint8_t directly, so that users go through
861// Incr/Decr/SetToZero/SetToOne to manipulate it, so that the saturation and
862// lack of over/underflow is always respected.
863class SaturatedUint8 {
864 public:
865 SaturatedUint8() = default;
866
867 void Incr() {
868 if (V8_LIKELY(val != kMax)) {
869 val++;
870 }
871 }
872 void Decr() {
873 if (V8_LIKELY(val != 0 && val != kMax)) {
874 val--;
875 }
876 }
877
878 void SetToZero() { val = 0; }
879 void SetToOne() { val = 1; }
880
881 bool IsZero() const { return val == 0; }
882 bool IsOne() const { return val == 1; }
883 bool IsSaturated() const { return val == kMax; }
884 uint8_t Get() const { return val; }
885
886 SaturatedUint8& operator+=(const SaturatedUint8& other) {
887 uint32_t sum = val;
888 sum += other.val;
889 val = static_cast<uint8_t>(std::min<uint32_t>(sum, kMax));
890 return *this;
891 }
892
893 static SaturatedUint8 FromSize(size_t value) {
894 uint8_t val = static_cast<uint8_t>(std::min<size_t>(value, kMax));
895 return SaturatedUint8{val};
896 }
897
898 private:
899 explicit SaturatedUint8(uint8_t val) : val(val) {}
900 uint8_t val = 0;
901 static constexpr uint8_t kMax = std::numeric_limits<uint8_t>::max();
902};
903
904// underlying_operation<> is used to extract the operation type from OpMaskT
905// classes used in Operation::Is<> and Operation::TryCast<>.
906template <typename T>
907struct underlying_operation {
908 using type = T;
909};
910template <typename T, uint64_t M, uint64_t V>
911struct underlying_operation<OpMaskT<T, M, V>> {
912 using type = T;
913};
914template <typename T>
915using underlying_operation_t = typename underlying_operation<T>::type;
916
917// Baseclass for all Turboshaft operations.
918// The `alignas(OpIndex)` is necessary because it is followed by an array of
919// `OpIndex` inputs.
920struct alignas(OpIndex) Operation {
921 struct IdentityMapper {
922 OpIndex Map(OpIndex index) { return index; }
923 OptionalOpIndex Map(OptionalOpIndex index) { return index; }
924 template <size_t N>
925 base::SmallVector<OpIndex, N> Map(base::Vector<const OpIndex> indices) {
926 return base::SmallVector<OpIndex, N>{indices};
927 }
928 };
929
930 const Opcode opcode;
931
932 // The number of uses of this operation in the current graph.
933 // Instead of overflowing, we saturate the value if it reaches the maximum. In
934 // this case, the true number of uses is unknown.
935 // We use such a small type to save memory and because nodes with a high
936 // number of uses are rare. Additionally, we usually only care if the number
937 // of uses is 0, 1 or bigger than 1.
938 SaturatedUint8 saturated_use_count;
939
940 const uint16_t input_count;
941
942 // The inputs are stored adjacent in memory, right behind the `Operation`
943 // object.
944 base::Vector<const OpIndex> inputs() const;
945 V8_INLINE OpIndex input(size_t i) const { return inputs()[i]; }
946
947 static size_t StorageSlotCount(Opcode opcode, size_t input_count);
948 size_t StorageSlotCount() const {
949 return StorageSlotCount(opcode, input_count);
950 }
951
952 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const;
953 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
954 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const;
955
956 template <class Op>
957 bool Is() const {
958 if constexpr (std::is_base_of_v<Operation, Op>) {
959 return opcode == Op::opcode;
960 } else {
961 // Otherwise this must be OpMaskT.
962 return IsOpmask<Op>();
963 }
964 }
965 template <class Op>
966 underlying_operation_t<Op>& Cast() {
967 DCHECK(Is<Op>());
968 return *static_cast<underlying_operation_t<Op>*>(this);
969 }
970 template <class Op>
971 const underlying_operation_t<Op>& Cast() const {
972 DCHECK(Is<Op>());
973 return *static_cast<const underlying_operation_t<Op>*>(this);
974 }
975 template <class Op>
976 const underlying_operation_t<Op>* TryCast() const {
977 if (!Is<Op>()) return nullptr;
978 return static_cast<const underlying_operation_t<Op>*>(this);
979 }
980 template <class Op>
981 underlying_operation_t<Op>* TryCast() {
982 if (!Is<Op>()) return nullptr;
983 return static_cast<underlying_operation_t<Op>*>(this);
984 }
985 OpEffects Effects() const;
986 bool IsBlockTerminator() const {
987 return turboshaft::IsBlockTerminator(opcode);
988 }
989 bool IsRequiredWhenUnused() const {
990 DCHECK_IMPLIES(IsBlockTerminator(), Effects().is_required_when_unused());
991 return Effects().is_required_when_unused();
992 }

994 std::string ToString() const;
995 void PrintInputs(std::ostream& os, const std::string& op_index_prefix) const;
996 void PrintOptions(std::ostream& os) const;
997
998 // Returns true if {this} is the only operation using {value}.
999 bool IsOnlyUserOf(const Operation& value, const Graph& graph) const;
1000
1001 void Print() const;
1002
1003 protected:
1004 // Operation objects store their inputs behind the object. Therefore, they can
1005 // only be constructed as part of a Graph.
1006 explicit Operation(Opcode opcode, size_t input_count)
1007 : opcode(opcode), input_count(input_count) {
1008 DCHECK_LE(input_count,
1009 std::numeric_limits<decltype(this->input_count)>::max());
1010 }
1011
1012 template <class OpmaskT>
1013 // A Turboshaft operation can be as small as 4 Bytes while Opmasks can span up
1014 // to 8 Bytes. Any mask larger than the operation it is compared with will
1015 // always have a mismatch in the initialized memory. Still, there can be some
1016 // uninitialized memory being compared as part of the 8 Byte comparison that
1017 // this function performs.
1018 V8_CLANG_NO_SANITIZE("memory") bool IsOpmask() const {
1019 static_assert(std::is_same_v<
1020 underlying_operation_t<OpmaskT>,
1021 typename OpMaskT<typename OpmaskT::operation, OpmaskT::mask,
1022 OpmaskT::value>::operation>);
1023 // We check with the given mask.
1024 uint64_t b;
1025 memcpy(&b, this, sizeof(uint64_t));
1026 b &= OpmaskT::mask;
1027 return b == OpmaskT::value;
1028 }
1029
1030 Operation(const Operation&) = delete;
1031 Operation& operator=(const Operation&) = delete;
1032};

1037};

1039V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
1040 OperationPrintStyle op);
1041inline std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Operation& op) {
1042 return os << OperationPrintStyle{op};
1043}

1050// Determine if an operation declares `effects`, which means that its
1051// effects are static and don't depend on inputs or options.
1052template <class Op, class = void>
1053struct HasStaticEffects : std::bool_constant<false> {};
1054template <class Op>
1055struct HasStaticEffects<Op, std::void_t<decltype(Op::effects)>>
1056 : std::bool_constant<true> {};
1057
1058// This template knows the complete type of the operation and is plugged into
1059// the inheritance hierarchy. It removes boilerplate from the concrete
1060// `Operation` subclasses, defining everything that can be expressed
1061// generically. It overshadows many methods from `Operation` with ones that
1062// exploit additional static information.
1063template <class Derived>
1064struct OperationT : Operation {
1065 // Enable concise base-constructor call in derived struct.
1066 using Base = OperationT;
1067
1068 static const Opcode opcode;
1069
1070 static constexpr OpEffects Effects() { return Derived::effects; }
1071 static constexpr bool IsBlockTerminator() {
1072 return turboshaft::IsBlockTerminator(opcode);
1073 }
1074 bool IsRequiredWhenUnused() const {
1075 return IsBlockTerminator() ||
1076 derived_this().Effects().is_required_when_unused();
1077 }
1078
1079 static constexpr std::optional<OpEffects> EffectsIfStatic() {
1080 if constexpr (HasStaticEffects<Derived>::value) {
1081 return Derived::Effects();
1082 }
1083 return std::nullopt;
1084 }
1085
1086 Derived& derived_this() { return *static_cast<Derived*>(this); }
1087 const Derived& derived_this() const {
1088 return *static_cast<const Derived*>(this);
1089 }
1090
1091 // Shadow Operation::inputs to exploit static knowledge about object size.
1092 base::Vector<OpIndex> inputs() {
1093 return {reinterpret_cast<OpIndex*>(reinterpret_cast<char*>(this) +
1094 sizeof(Derived)),
1095 derived_this().input_count};
1096 }
1097 base::Vector<const OpIndex> inputs() const {
1098 return {reinterpret_cast<const OpIndex*>(
1099 reinterpret_cast<const char*>(this) + sizeof(Derived)),
1100 derived_this().input_count};
1101 }
1102
1103 V8_INLINE OpIndex& input(size_t i) { return derived_this().inputs()[i]; }
1104 // TODO(chromium:331100916): remove this V<Any> overload once all users use
1105 // the more specific V<T> overload.
1106 V8_INLINE V<Any> input(size_t i) const { return derived_this().inputs()[i]; }
1107 template <typename T>
1108 V8_INLINE V<T> input(size_t i) const {
1109 return V<T>::Cast(derived_this().inputs()[i]);
1110 }
1111
1112 static size_t StorageSlotCount(size_t input_count) {
1113 // The operation size in bytes is:
1114 // `sizeof(Derived) + input_count*sizeof(OpIndex)`.
1115 // This is an optimized computation of:
1116 // round_up(size_in_bytes / sizeof(StorageSlot))
1117 constexpr size_t r = sizeof(OperationStorageSlot) / sizeof(OpIndex);
1118 static_assert(sizeof(OperationStorageSlot) % sizeof(OpIndex) == 0);
1119 static_assert(sizeof(Derived) % sizeof(OpIndex) == 0);
1120 size_t result = std::max<size_t>(
1121 2, (r - 1 + sizeof(Derived) / sizeof(OpIndex) + input_count) / r);
1122 DCHECK_EQ(result, Operation::StorageSlotCount(opcode, input_count));
1123 return result;
1124 }
1125 size_t StorageSlotCount() const { return StorageSlotCount(input_count); }
1126
1127 template <class... Args>
1128 static Derived& New(Graph* graph, size_t input_count, Args... args) {
1129 OperationStorageSlot* ptr =
1130 AllocateOpStorage(graph, StorageSlotCount(input_count));
1131 Derived* result = new (ptr) Derived(args...);
1132#ifdef DEBUG
1133 result->Validate(*graph);
1134 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation> storage(get_zone(graph));
1135 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> expected =
1136 result->inputs_rep(storage);
1137 // TODO(mliedtke): DCHECK that expected and inputs are of the same size
1138 // and adapt inputs_rep() to always emit a representation for all inputs.
1139 size_t end = std::min<size_t>(expected.size(), result->input_count);
1140 for (size_t i = 0; i < end; ++i) {
1141 if (expected[i] == MaybeRegisterRepresentation::None()) continue;
1142 DCHECK(ValidOpInputRep(*graph, result->inputs()[i],
1143 RegisterRepresentation(expected[i])));
1144 }
1145#endif
1146 // If this DCHECK fails, then the number of inputs specified in the
1147 // operation constructor and in the static New function disagree.
1148 DCHECK_EQ(input_count, result->Operation::input_count);
1149 return *result;
1150 }
1151
1152 template <class... Args>
1153 static Derived& New(Graph* graph, ShadowyOpIndexVectorWrapper inputs,
1154 Args... args) {
1155 return New(graph, inputs.size(), inputs, args...);
1156 }
1157
1158 explicit OperationT(size_t input_count) : Operation(opcode, input_count) {
1159 static_assert((std::is_base_of<OperationT, Derived>::value));
1160#if !V8_CC_MSVC
1161 static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable<Derived>::value);
1162#endif // !V8_CC_MSVC
1163 static_assert(std::is_trivially_destructible<Derived>::value);
1164 }
1165 explicit OperationT(ShadowyOpIndexVectorWrapper inputs)
1166 : OperationT(inputs.size()) {
1167 this->inputs().OverwriteWith(
1168 static_cast<base::Vector<const OpIndex>>(inputs));
1169 }
1170
1171 bool EqualsForGVN(const Base& other) const {
1172 // By default, GVN only removed identical Operations. However, some
1173 // Operations (like DeoptimizeIf) can be GVNed when a dominating
1174 // similar-but-not-identical one exists. In that case, the Operation should
1175 // redefine EqualsForGVN, so that GVN knows which inputs or options of the
1176 // Operation to ignore (you should also probably redefine hash_value,
1177 // otherwise GVN won't even try to call EqualsForGVN).
1178 return derived_this() == other.derived_this();
1179 }
1180 bool operator==(const Base& other) const {
1181 return derived_this().inputs() == other.derived_this().inputs() &&
1182 derived_this().options() == other.derived_this().options();
1183 }
1184 template <typename... Args>
1185 size_t HashWithOptions(const Args&... args) const {
1186 return fast_hash_combine(opcode, derived_this().inputs(), args...);
1187 }
1188 size_t hash_value(
1189 HashingStrategy strategy = HashingStrategy::kDefault) const {
1190 return HashWithOptions(derived_this().options());
1191 }
1192
1193 void PrintInputs(std::ostream& os, const std::string& op_index_prefix) const {
1194 os << "(";
1195 bool first = true;
1196 for (OpIndex input : inputs()) {
1197 if (!first) os << ", ";
1198 first = false;
1199 os << op_index_prefix << input.id();
1200 }
1201 os << ")";
1202 }
1203
1204 void PrintOptions(std::ostream& os) const {
1205 const auto& options = derived_this().options();
1206 constexpr size_t options_count =
1207 std::tuple_size<std::remove_reference_t<decltype(options)>>::value;
1208 if (options_count == 0) {
1209 return;
1210 }
1211 PrintOptionsHelper(os, options, std::make_index_sequence<options_count>());
1212 }
1213
1214 // Check graph invariants for this operation. Will be invoked in debug mode
1215 // immediately upon construction.
1216 // Concrete Operator classes are expected to re-define it.
1217 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {}
1218
1219 private:
1220 template <class... T, size_t... I>
1221 static void PrintOptionsHelper(std::ostream& os,
1222 const std::tuple<T...>& options,
1223 std::index_sequence<I...>) {
1224 os << "[";
1225 bool first = true;
1226 USE(first);
1227 ((first ? (first = false, os << std::get<I>(options))
1228 : os << ", " << std::get<I>(options)),
1229 ...);
1230 os << "]";
1231 }
1232
1233 // All Operations have to define the outputs_rep function, to which
1234 // Operation::outputs_rep() will forward, based on their opcode. If you forget
1235 // to define it, then Operation::outputs_rep() would forward to itself,
1236 // resulting in an infinite loop. To avoid this, we define here in OperationT
1237 // a private version outputs_rep (with no implementation): if an operation
1238 // forgets to define outputs_rep, then Operation::outputs_rep() tries to call
1239 // this private version, which fails at compile time.
1240 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const;
1241
1242 // Returns a vector of the input representations.
1243 // The passed in {storage} can be used to store the underlying data.
1244 // The returned vector might be smaller than the input_count in which case the
1245 // additional inputs are assumed to have no register representation.
1246 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
1247 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const;
1248};
1249
1250template <size_t InputCount, class Derived>
1251struct FixedArityOperationT : OperationT<Derived> {
1252 // Enable concise base access in derived struct.
1253 using Base = FixedArityOperationT;
1254
1255 // Shadow Operation::input_count to exploit static knowledge.
1256 static constexpr uint16_t input_count = InputCount;
1257
1258 template <class... Args>
1259 explicit FixedArityOperationT(Args... args)
1260 : OperationT<Derived>(InputCount) {
1261 static_assert(sizeof...(Args) == InputCount, "wrong number of inputs");
1262 size_t i = 0;
1263 OpIndex* inputs = this->inputs().begin();
1264 ((inputs[i++] = args), ...);
1265 }
1266
1267 // Redefine the input initialization to tell C++ about the static input size.
1268 template <class... Args>
1269 static Derived& New(Graph* graph, Args... args) {
1270 Derived& result =
1271 OperationT<Derived>::New(graph, InputCount, std::move(args)...);
1272 return result;
1273 }
1274
1275 template <typename Fn, typename Mapper, size_t... InputI, size_t... OptionI>
1276 V8_INLINE auto ExplodeImpl(Fn fn, Mapper& mapper,
1277 std::index_sequence<InputI...>,
1278 std::index_sequence<OptionI...>) const {
1279 auto options = this->derived_this().options();
1280 USE(options);
1281 return fn(mapper.Map(this->input(InputI))...,
1282 std::get<OptionI>(options)...);
1283 }
1284
1285 template <typename Fn, typename Mapper>
1286 V8_INLINE auto Explode(Fn fn, Mapper& mapper) const {
1287 return ExplodeImpl(
1288 fn, mapper, std::make_index_sequence<input_count>(),
1289 std::make_index_sequence<
1290 std::tuple_size_v<decltype(this->derived_this().options())>>());
1291 }
1292};
1293
1294#define SUPPORTED_OPERATIONS_LIST(V) \
1295 V(float32_round_down, Float32RoundDown) \
1296 V(float64_round_down, Float64RoundDown) \
1297 V(float32_round_up, Float32RoundUp) \
1298 V(float64_round_up, Float64RoundUp) \
1299 V(float32_round_to_zero, Float32RoundTruncate) \
1300 V(float64_round_to_zero, Float64RoundTruncate) \
1301 V(float32_round_ties_even, Float32RoundTiesEven) \
1302 V(float64_round_ties_even, Float64RoundTiesEven) \
1303 V(float64_round_ties_away, Float64RoundTiesAway) \
1304 V(int32_div_is_safe, Int32DivIsSafe) \
1305 V(uint32_div_is_safe, Uint32DivIsSafe) \
1306 V(word32_shift_is_safe, Word32ShiftIsSafe) \
1307 V(word32_ctz, Word32Ctz) \
1308 V(word64_ctz, Word64Ctz) \
1309 V(word64_ctz_lowerable, Word64CtzLowerable) \
1310 V(word32_popcnt, Word32Popcnt) \
1311 V(word64_popcnt, Word64Popcnt) \
1312 V(word32_reverse_bits, Word32ReverseBits) \
1313 V(word64_reverse_bits, Word64ReverseBits) \

1327class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE SupportedOperations {
1328#define DECLARE_FIELD(name, machine_name) bool name##_;
1329#define DECLARE_GETTER(name, machine_name) \
1330 static bool name() { \
1331 if constexpr (DEBUG_BOOL) { \
1332 base::SpinningMutexGuard lock(mutex_.Pointer()); \
1333 DCHECK(initialized_); \
1334 } \
1335 return instance_.name##_; \
1336 }
1337
1338 public:
1339 static void Initialize();
1340 static bool IsUnalignedLoadSupported(MemoryRepresentation repr);
1341 static bool IsUnalignedStoreSupported(MemoryRepresentation repr);
1342 SUPPORTED_OPERATIONS_LIST(DECLARE_GETTER)
1343
1344 private:
1345 SUPPORTED_OPERATIONS_LIST(DECLARE_FIELD)
1346
1347 static bool initialized_;
1348 static base::LazySpinningMutex mutex_;
1349 static SupportedOperations instance_;
1350
1351#undef DECLARE_FIELD
1352#undef DECLARE_GETTER
1353};

1355template <RegisterRepresentation::Enum... reps>
1356base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> RepVector() {
1357 static constexpr std::array<RegisterRepresentation, sizeof...(reps)>
1358 rep_array{RegisterRepresentation{reps}...};
1359 return base::VectorOf(rep_array);
1360}
1361
1362template <MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Enum... reps>
1363base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> MaybeRepVector() {
1364 static constexpr std::array<MaybeRegisterRepresentation, sizeof...(reps)>
1365 rep_array{MaybeRegisterRepresentation{reps}...};
1366 return base::VectorOf(rep_array);
1367}

1379// DeadOp is a special operation that can be used by analyzers to mark
1380// operations as being dead (typically, it should be used by calling the Graph's
1381// KillOperation method, which will Replace the old operation by a DeadOp).
1382// CopyingPhase and Analyzers should ignore Dead operations. A Dead operation
1383// should never be the input of a non-dead operation.
1384struct DeadOp : FixedArityOperationT<0, DeadOp> {
1385 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
1386
1387 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const { return {}; }
1388
1389 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
1390 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
1391 return {};
1392 }
1393
1394 auto options() const { return std::tuple{}; }
1395};

1399 OpEffects().RequiredWhenUnused().CanLeaveCurrentFunction();

1404 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {

1406 }
1407
1408 V<String> message() const { return Base::input<String>(0); }
1409
1410 explicit AbortCSADcheckOp(V<String> message) : Base(message) {}
1411
1412 auto options() const { return std::tuple{}; }
1413};

1532// Word32SignHint is a type-hint used during Maglev->Turboshaft
1533// translation to avoid having multiple values being used as both Int32 and
1534// Uint32: for such cases, Maglev has explicit conversions, and it's helpful to
1535// also have them in Turboshaft. Eventually, Word32SignHint is just a
1536// nop in Turboshaft, since as far as Machine level graph is concerned, both
1537// Int32 and Uint32 are just Word32 registers.
1538struct Word32SignHintOp : FixedArityOperationT<1, Word32SignHintOp> {
1539 enum class Sign : bool { kSigned, kUnsigned };
1540 Sign sign;
1541
1542 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
1543 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
1544 return RepVector<RegisterRepresentation::Word32()>();
1545 }
1546
1547 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
1548 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
1549 return MaybeRepVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation::Word32()>();
1550 }
1551
1552 V<Word32> input() const { return Base::input<Word32>(0); }
1553
1554 Word32SignHintOp(V<Word32> input, Sign sign) : Base(input), sign(sign) {}
1555
1556 auto options() const { return std::tuple{sign}; }
1557};
1558V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
1559 Word32SignHintOp::Sign sign);

1561struct WordBinopOp : FixedArityOperationT<2, WordBinopOp> {
1562 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
1563 kAdd,
1564 kMul,
1565 kSignedMulOverflownBits,
1566 kUnsignedMulOverflownBits,
1567 kBitwiseAnd,
1568 kBitwiseOr,
1569 kBitwiseXor,
1570 kSub,
1571 kSignedDiv,
1572 kUnsignedDiv,
1573 kSignedMod,
1574 kUnsignedMod,
1575 };
1576 Kind kind;
1577 WordRepresentation rep;
1578
1579 // We must avoid division by 0.
1580 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects().CanDependOnChecks();
1581 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
1582 return base::VectorOf(static_cast<const RegisterRepresentation*>(&rep), 1);
1583 }
1584
1585 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
1586 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
1587 return InputsRepFactory::PairOf(rep);
1588 }
1589
1590 template <class WordType = Word>
1591 V<WordType> left() const
1592 requires(IsWord<WordType>())
1593 {
1594 return input<WordType>(0);
1595 }
1596 template <class WordType = Word>
1597 V<WordType> right() const
1598 requires(IsWord<WordType>())
1599 {
1600 return input<WordType>(1);
1601 }
1602
1603 bool IsCommutative() const { return IsCommutative(kind); }
1604
1605 static bool IsCommutative(Kind kind) {
1606 switch (kind) {
1607 case Kind::kAdd:
1608 case Kind::kMul:
1609 case Kind::kSignedMulOverflownBits:
1610 case Kind::kUnsignedMulOverflownBits:
1611 case Kind::kBitwiseAnd:
1612 case Kind::kBitwiseOr:
1613 case Kind::kBitwiseXor:
1614 return true;
1615 case Kind::kSub:
1616 case Kind::kSignedDiv:
1617 case Kind::kUnsignedDiv:
1618 case Kind::kSignedMod:
1619 case Kind::kUnsignedMod:
1620 return false;
1621 }
1622 }
1623
1624 static bool IsAssociative(Kind kind) {
1625 switch (kind) {
1626 case Kind::kAdd:
1627 case Kind::kMul:
1628 case Kind::kBitwiseAnd:
1629 case Kind::kBitwiseOr:
1630 case Kind::kBitwiseXor:
1631 return true;
1632 case Kind::kSignedMulOverflownBits:
1633 case Kind::kUnsignedMulOverflownBits:
1634 case Kind::kSub:
1635 case Kind::kSignedDiv:
1636 case Kind::kUnsignedDiv:
1637 case Kind::kSignedMod:
1638 case Kind::kUnsignedMod:
1639 return false;
1640 }
1641 }
1642 // The Word32 and Word64 versions of the operator compute the same result when
1643 // truncated to 32 bit.
1644 static bool AllowsWord64ToWord32Truncation(Kind kind) {
1645 switch (kind) {
1646 case Kind::kAdd:
1647 case Kind::kMul:
1648 case Kind::kBitwiseAnd:
1649 case Kind::kBitwiseOr:
1650 case Kind::kBitwiseXor:
1651 case Kind::kSub:
1652 return true;
1653 case Kind::kSignedMulOverflownBits:
1654 case Kind::kUnsignedMulOverflownBits:
1655 case Kind::kSignedDiv:
1656 case Kind::kUnsignedDiv:
1657 case Kind::kSignedMod:
1658 case Kind::kUnsignedMod:
1659 return false;
1660 }
1661 }
1662
1663 WordBinopOp(V<Word> left, V<Word> right, Kind kind, WordRepresentation rep)
1664 : Base(left, right), kind(kind), rep(rep) {}
1665
1666 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, rep}; }
1667 void PrintOptions(std::ostream& os) const;
1668};

1813struct OverflowCheckedBinopOp
1814 : FixedArityOperationT<2, OverflowCheckedBinopOp> {
1815 static constexpr int kValueIndex = 0;
1816 static constexpr int kOverflowIndex = 1;
1817
1818 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
1819 kSignedAdd,
1820 kSignedMul,
1821 kSignedSub,
1822 };
1823 Kind kind;
1824 WordRepresentation rep;
1825
1826 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
1827 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
1828 switch (rep.value()) {
1829 case WordRepresentation::Word32():
1830 return RepVector<RegisterRepresentation::Word32(),
1831 RegisterRepresentation::Word32()>();
1832 case WordRepresentation::Word64():
1833 return RepVector<RegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
1834 RegisterRepresentation::Word32()>();
1835 }
1836 }
1837
1838 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
1839 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
1840 return InputsRepFactory::PairOf(rep);
1841 }
1842
1843 V<Word> left() const { return input<Word>(0); }
1844 V<Word> right() const { return input<Word>(1); }
1845
1846 static bool IsCommutative(Kind kind) {
1847 switch (kind) {
1848 case Kind::kSignedAdd:
1849 case Kind::kSignedMul:
1850 return true;
1851 case Kind::kSignedSub:
1852 return false;
1853 }
1854 }
1855
1856 OverflowCheckedBinopOp(V<Word> left, V<Word> right, Kind kind,
1857 WordRepresentation rep)
1858 : Base(left, right), kind(kind), rep(rep) {}
1859
1860 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, rep}; }
1861 void PrintOptions(std::ostream& os) const;
1862};

1989struct ShiftOp : FixedArityOperationT<2, ShiftOp> {
1990 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
1991 kShiftRightArithmeticShiftOutZeros,
1992 kShiftRightArithmetic,
1993 kShiftRightLogical,
1994 kShiftLeft,
1995 kRotateRight,
1996 kRotateLeft
1997 };
1998 Kind kind;
1999 WordRepresentation rep;
2000
2001 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
2002 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2003 return base::VectorOf(static_cast<const RegisterRepresentation*>(&rep), 1);
2004 }
2005
2006 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
2007 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
2008 return InitVectorOf(storage,
2009 {static_cast<const RegisterRepresentation&>(rep),
2010 RegisterRepresentation::Word32()});
2011 }
2012
2013 template <typename WordT = Word>
2014 requires(IsWord<WordT>())
2015 V<WordT> left() const {
2016 DCHECK(IsValidTypeFor<WordT>(rep));
2017 return input<WordT>(0);
2018 }
2019 V<Word32> right() const { return input<Word32>(1); }
2020
2021 bool IsRightShift() const { return IsRightShift(kind); }
2022
2023 static bool IsRightShift(Kind kind) {
2024 switch (kind) {
2025 case Kind::kShiftRightArithmeticShiftOutZeros:
2026 case Kind::kShiftRightArithmetic:
2027 case Kind::kShiftRightLogical:
2028 return true;
2029 case Kind::kShiftLeft:
2030 case Kind::kRotateRight:
2031 case Kind::kRotateLeft:
2032 return false;
2033 }
2034 }
2035 // The Word32 and Word64 versions of the operator compute the same result when
2036 // truncated to 32 bit.
2037 static bool AllowsWord64ToWord32Truncation(Kind kind) {
2038 switch (kind) {
2039 case Kind::kShiftLeft:
2040 return true;
2041 case Kind::kShiftRightArithmeticShiftOutZeros:
2042 case Kind::kShiftRightArithmetic:
2043 case Kind::kShiftRightLogical:
2044 case Kind::kRotateRight:
2045 case Kind::kRotateLeft:
2046 return false;
2047 }
2048 }
2049
2050 ShiftOp(V<Word> left, V<Word32> right, Kind kind, WordRepresentation rep)
2051 : Base(left, right), kind(kind), rep(rep) {}
2052
2053 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, rep}; }
2054};
2055V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
2056 ShiftOp::Kind kind);

2058struct ComparisonOp : FixedArityOperationT<2, ComparisonOp> {
2059 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
2060 kEqual,
2061 kSignedLessThan,
2062 kSignedLessThanOrEqual,
2063 kUnsignedLessThan,
2064 kUnsignedLessThanOrEqual
2065 };
2066 Kind kind;
2067 RegisterRepresentation rep;
2068
2069 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
2070 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2071 return RepVector<RegisterRepresentation::Word32()>();
2072 }
2073
2074 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
2075 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
2076 return InputsRepFactory::PairOf(rep);
2077 }
2078
2079 static bool IsCommutative(Kind kind) { return kind == Kind::kEqual; }
2080
2081 template <typename T = Any>
2082 V<T> left() const {
2083 DCHECK(IsValidTypeFor<T>(rep));
2084 return input<T>(0);
2085 }
2086 template <typename T = Any>
2087 V<T> right() const {
2088 DCHECK(IsValidTypeFor<T>(rep));
2089 return input<T>(1);
2090 }
2091
2092 ComparisonOp(V<Any> left, V<Any> right, Kind kind, RegisterRepresentation rep)
2093 : Base(left, right), kind(kind), rep(rep) {}
2094
2095 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {
2096 if (kind == Kind::kEqual) {
2097 DCHECK(rep == any_of(RegisterRepresentation::Word32(),
2098 RegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
2099 RegisterRepresentation::Float32(),
2100 RegisterRepresentation::Float64(),
2101 RegisterRepresentation::Tagged()));
2102
2103 RegisterRepresentation input_rep = rep;
2104#ifdef V8_COMPRESS_POINTERS
2105 // In the presence of pointer compression, we only compare the lower
2106 // 32bit.
2107 if (input_rep == RegisterRepresentation::Tagged()) {
2108 input_rep = RegisterRepresentation::Compressed();
2109 }
2110#endif // V8_COMPRESS_POINTERS
2111 DCHECK(ValidOpInputRep(graph, left(), input_rep));
2112 DCHECK(ValidOpInputRep(graph, right(), input_rep));
2113 USE(input_rep);
2114 } else {
2115 DCHECK_EQ(rep, any_of(RegisterRepresentation::Word32(),
2116 RegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
2117 RegisterRepresentation::Float32(),
2118 RegisterRepresentation::Float64()));
2119 DCHECK_IMPLIES(
2120 rep == any_of(RegisterRepresentation::Float32(),
2121 RegisterRepresentation::Float64()),
2122 kind == any_of(Kind::kSignedLessThan, Kind::kSignedLessThanOrEqual));
2123 }
2124 }
2125 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, rep}; }
2126};
2127V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
2128 ComparisonOp::Kind kind);
2129DEFINE_MULTI_SWITCH_INTEGRAL(ComparisonOp::Kind, 8)
2130
2131struct ChangeOp : FixedArityOperationT<1, ChangeOp> {
2132 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
2133 // convert between different floating-point types. Note that the
2134 // Float64->Float32 conversion is truncating.
2135 kFloatConversion,
2136 // overflow guaranteed to result in the minimal integer
2137 kSignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin,
2138 kUnsignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin,
2139 // JS semantics float64 to word32 truncation
2140 // https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-touint32
2141 kJSFloatTruncate,
2142 // convert float64 to float16, then bitcast word32. Used for storing into
2143 // Float16Array and Math.fround16.
2144 kJSFloat16TruncateWithBitcast,
2145 // convert (un)signed integer to floating-point value
2146 kSignedToFloat,
2147 kUnsignedToFloat,
2148 // extract half of a float64 value
2149 kExtractHighHalf,
2150 kExtractLowHalf,
2151 // increase bit-width for unsigned integer values
2152 kZeroExtend,
2153 // increase bid-width for signed integer values
2154 kSignExtend,
2155 // truncate word64 to word32
2156 kTruncate,
2157 // preserve bits, change meaning
2158 kBitcast
2159 };
2160 // Violated assumptions result in undefined behavior.
2161 enum class Assumption : uint8_t {
2162 kNoAssumption,
2163 // Used for conversions from floating-point to integer, assumes that the
2164 // value doesn't exceed the integer range.
2165 kNoOverflow,
2166 // Assume that the original value can be recovered by a corresponding
2167 // reverse transformation.
2168 kReversible,
2169 };
2170 Kind kind;
2171 // Reversible means undefined behavior if value cannot be represented
2172 // precisely.
2173 Assumption assumption;
2174 RegisterRepresentation from;
2175 RegisterRepresentation to;
2176
2177 // Returns true if change<kind>(change<reverse_kind>(a)) == a for all a.
2178 // This assumes that change<reverse_kind> uses the inverted {from} and {to}
2179 // representations, i.e. the input to the inner change op has the same
2180 // representation as the result of the outer change op.
2181 static bool IsReversible(Kind kind, Assumption assumption,
2182 RegisterRepresentation from,
2183 RegisterRepresentation to, Kind reverse_kind,
2184 bool signalling_nan_possible) {
2185 switch (kind) {
2186 case Kind::kFloatConversion:
2187 return from == RegisterRepresentation::Float32() &&
2188 to == RegisterRepresentation::Float64() &&
2189 reverse_kind == Kind::kFloatConversion &&
2190 !signalling_nan_possible;
2191 case Kind::kSignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin:
2192 return assumption == Assumption::kReversible &&
2193 reverse_kind == Kind::kSignedToFloat;
2194 case Kind::kUnsignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin:
2195 return assumption == Assumption::kReversible &&
2196 reverse_kind == Kind::kUnsignedToFloat;
2197 case Kind::kJSFloatTruncate:
2198 return false;
2199 case Kind::kJSFloat16TruncateWithBitcast:
2200 return false;
2201 case Kind::kSignedToFloat:
2202 if (from == RegisterRepresentation::Word32() &&
2203 to == RegisterRepresentation::Float64()) {
2204 return reverse_kind == any_of(Kind::kSignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin,
2205 Kind::kJSFloatTruncate);
2206 } else {
2207 return assumption == Assumption::kReversible &&
2208 reverse_kind ==
2209 any_of(Kind::kSignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin);
2210 }
2211 case Kind::kUnsignedToFloat:
2212 if (from == RegisterRepresentation::Word32() &&
2213 to == RegisterRepresentation::Float64()) {
2214 return reverse_kind ==
2215 any_of(Kind::kUnsignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin,
2216 Kind::kJSFloatTruncate);
2217 } else {
2218 return assumption == Assumption::kReversible &&
2219 reverse_kind == Kind::kUnsignedFloatTruncateOverflowToMin;
2220 }
2221 case Kind::kExtractHighHalf:
2222 case Kind::kExtractLowHalf:
2223 return false;
2224 case Kind::kZeroExtend:
2225 case Kind::kSignExtend:
2226 DCHECK_EQ(from, RegisterRepresentation::Word32());
2227 DCHECK_EQ(to, RegisterRepresentation::Word64());
2228 return reverse_kind == Kind::kTruncate;
2229 case Kind::kTruncate:
2230 DCHECK_EQ(from, RegisterRepresentation::Word64());
2231 DCHECK_EQ(to, RegisterRepresentation::Word32());
2232 return reverse_kind == Kind::kBitcast;
2233 case Kind::kBitcast:
2234 return reverse_kind == Kind::kBitcast;
2235 }
2236 }
2237
2238 bool IsReversibleBy(Kind reverse_kind, bool signalling_nan_possible) const {
2239 return IsReversible(kind, assumption, from, to, reverse_kind,
2240 signalling_nan_possible);
2241 }
2242
2243 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
2244 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2245 return base::VectorOf(&to, 1);
2246 }
2247
2248 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
2249 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
2250 return InputsRepFactory::SingleRep(from);
2251 }
2252
2253 template <typename Type = Untagged>
2254 requires IsUntagged<Type>
2255 V<Type> input() const {
2256 DCHECK(IsValidTypeFor<Type>(from));
2257 return Base::input<Type>(0);
2258 }
2259
2260 ChangeOp(V<Untagged> input, Kind kind, Assumption assumption,
2261 RegisterRepresentation from, RegisterRepresentation to)
2262 : Base(input), kind(kind), assumption(assumption), from(from), to(to) {}
2263
2264 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {
2265 DCHECK_NE(from, RegisterRepresentation::Tagged());
2266 DCHECK_NE(to, RegisterRepresentation::Tagged());
2267 // Bitcasts from and to Tagged should use a TaggedBitcast instead (which has
2268 // different effects, since it's unsafe to reorder such bitcasts accross
2269 // GCs).
2270 }
2271 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, assumption, from, to}; }
2272};
2273V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
2274 ChangeOp::Kind kind);
2275V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os,
2276 ChangeOp::Assumption assumption);
2277DEFINE_MULTI_SWITCH_INTEGRAL(ChangeOp::Kind, 16)
2278DEFINE_MULTI_SWITCH_INTEGRAL(ChangeOp::Assumption, 4)

2280struct ChangeOrDeoptOp : FixedArityOperationT<2, ChangeOrDeoptOp> {
2281 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
2282 kUint32ToInt32,
2283 kInt64ToInt32,

2286 kFloat64ToInt32,

2296 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2297 switch (kind) {

2299 case Kind::kInt64ToInt32:
2300 case Kind::kUint64ToInt32:
2301 case Kind::kFloat64ToInt32:
2302 case Kind::kFloat64ToUint32:

2317 case Kind::kInt64ToInt32:

2321 case Kind::kFloat64ToInt32:
2322 case Kind::kFloat64ToUint32:

2327 }

2333 CheckForMinusZeroMode minus_zero_mode,

2336 kind(kind),
2337 minus_zero_mode(minus_zero_mode),
2338 feedback(feedback) {}
2339
2340 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {
2341 DCHECK(Get(graph, frame_state()).Is<FrameStateOp>());
2342 }
2343
2344 auto options() const { return std::tuple{kind, minus_zero_mode, feedback}; }
2345};

2349// Perform a conversion and return a pair of the result and a bit if it was

2413struct TaggedBitcastOp : FixedArityOperationT<1, TaggedBitcastOp> {
2414 enum class Kind : uint8_t {
2415 kSmi, // This is a bitcast from a Word to a Smi or from a Smi to a Word
2416 kHeapObject, // This is a bitcast from or to a Heap Object
2417 kTagAndSmiBits, // This is a bitcast where only access to the tag and the
2418 // smi bits (if it's a smi) are valid
2419 kAny
2420 };
2421 Kind kind;
2422 RegisterRepresentation from;
2423 RegisterRepresentation to;
2424
2425 OpEffects Effects() const {
2426 switch (kind) {
2427 case Kind::kSmi:
2428 case Kind::kTagAndSmiBits:
2429 return OpEffects();
2430 case Kind::kHeapObject:
2431 case Kind::kAny:
2432 // Due to moving GC, converting from or to pointers doesn't commute with
2433 // GC.
2434 return OpEffects().CanDoRawHeapAccess();
2435 }
2436 }
2437
2438 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2439 return base::VectorOf(&to, 1);
2440 }
2441
2442 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
2443 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
2444 return InputsRepFactory::SingleRep(from);
2445 }
2446
2447 OpIndex input() const { return Base::input(0); }
2448
2449 TaggedBitcastOp(OpIndex input, RegisterRepresentation from,
2450 RegisterRepresentation to, Kind kind)
2451 : Base(input), kind(kind), from(from), to(to) {}
2452
2453 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {
2454 if (kind == Kind::kSmi) {
2455 DCHECK((from.IsWord() && to.IsTaggedOrCompressed()) ||
2456 (from.IsTaggedOrCompressed() && to.IsWord()));
2457 DCHECK_IMPLIES(from == RegisterRepresentation::Word64() ||
2458 to == RegisterRepresentation::Word64(),
2459 Is64());
2460 } else {
2461 // TODO(nicohartmann@): Without implicit trucation, the first case might
2462 // not be correct anymore.
2463 DCHECK((from.IsWord() && to == RegisterRepresentation::Tagged()) ||
2464 (from == RegisterRepresentation::Tagged() &&
2465 to == RegisterRepresentation::WordPtr()) ||
2466 (from == RegisterRepresentation::Compressed() &&
2467 to == RegisterRepresentation::Word32()));
2468 }
2469 }
2470 auto options() const { return std::tuple{from, to, kind}; }
2471};
2472std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, TaggedBitcastOp::Kind assumption);

2474struct SelectOp : FixedArityOperationT<3, SelectOp> {
2475 enum class Implementation : uint8_t { kBranch, kCMove };
2476
2477 RegisterRepresentation rep;
2478 BranchHint hint;
2479 Implementation implem;
2480
2481 static constexpr OpEffects effects = OpEffects();
2482 base::Vector<const RegisterRepresentation> outputs_rep() const {
2483 return base::VectorOf(&rep, 1);
2484 }
2485
2486 base::Vector<const MaybeRegisterRepresentation> inputs_rep(
2487 ZoneVector<MaybeRegisterRepresentation>& storage) const {
2488 return InitVectorOf(storage, {RegisterRepresentation::Word32(), rep, rep});
2489 }
2490
2491 SelectOp(V<Word32> cond, V<Any> vtrue, V<Any> vfalse,
2492 RegisterRepresentation rep, BranchHint hint, Implementation implem)
2493 : Base(cond, vtrue, vfalse), rep(rep), hint(hint), implem(implem) {}
2494
2495 void Validate(const Graph& graph) const {
2496 DCHECK_IMPLIES(implem == Implementation::kCMove,
2497 (rep == RegisterRepresentation::Word32() &&
2498 SupportedOperations::word32_select()) ||
2499 (rep == RegisterRepresentation::Word64() &&
2500 SupportedOperations::word64_select()) ||
2501 (rep == RegisterRepresentation::Float32() &&
2502 SupportedOperations::float32_select()) ||
2503 (rep == RegisterRepresentation::Float64() &&
2504 SupportedOperations::float64_select()));
2505 }
2506
2507 V<Word32> cond() const { return input<Word32>(0); }
2508 V<Any> vtrue() const { return input<Any>(1); }
2509 V<Any> vfalse() const { return input<Any>(2); }
2510
2511 auto options() const { return std::tuple{rep, hint, implem}; }
2512};

2514 SelectOp::Implementation kind);
